Examples
	• Flower Species Classification 
	• Face Recognition 
	• Animal Classification 
	• Medical Diagnosis 

3. Working of QDA
Step 1: Collect the Dataset
Prepare the labeled dataset.
Example
Height	Weight	Class
160	55	Class A
170	70	Class B
180	85	Class C

Step 2: Calculate the Mean of Each Class
Find the average value of each feature for every class.
Example
Mean of Class A = 162
Mean of Class B = 171
Mean of Class C = 181

Step 3: Calculate Covariance Matrix
Unlike LDA, QDA calculates a separate covariance matrix for each class.
Example
	• Covariance of Class A 
	• Covariance of Class B 
	• Covariance of Class C 
This allows each class to have a different shape and spread.

Step 4: Compute Quadratic Decision Boundary
Using the class means and covariance matrices, QDA creates curved (quadratic) boundaries that better separate nonlinear classes.

Step 5: Calculate Posterior Probability
The probability of the new observation belonging to each class is calculated.

Step 6: Assign the Final Class
The class with the highest posterior probability is selected as the prediction.

Mathematical Formula
The discriminant function used in QDA is:

δ_k (x)=−1/2  ln⁡∣ Σ_k∣−1/2 (x−μ_k )^T Σ_k^(−1) (x−μ_k )+ln⁡(π_k )
 
Where:
	• μₖ = Mean vector of class k 
	• Σₖ = Covariance matrix of class k 
	• πₖ = Prior probability of class k 
	• x = Input feature vector 

Example
Suppose a hospital wants to classify patients into:
	• Healthy 
	• Diabetes 
	• Heart Disease 
Input Features
	• Age = 50 
	• Blood Pressure = 150 
	• Cholesterol = 240 
Since the classes have different distributions, QDA creates curved decision boundaries and predicts:
Prediction = Heart Disease

Advantages
	• Handles nonlinear class boundaries effectively. 
	• More flexible than LDA. 
	• Uses separate covariance matrices for each class. 
	• Produces high accuracy when class distributions differ. 
	• Suitable for complex classification problems. 

Disadvantages
	• Requires more training data than LDA. 
	• More computationally expensive. 
	• Sensitive to outliers. 
	• May overfit small datasets. 
	• Assumes each class follows a Gaussian (normal) distribution. 

Applications
	• Medical Diagnosis 
	• Face Recognition 
	• Image Classification 
	• Financial Risk Analysis 
	• Speech Recognition 
	• Bioinformatics 
	• Pattern Recognition 
	• Customer Segmentation 

Binary QDA vs Multi-class QDA
Feature	Binary QDA	Multi-class QDA
Number of Classes	Two	More than Two
Covariance Matrices	One per class	One per class
Decision Boundary	Quadratic	Multiple Quadratic Boundaries
Example	Spam Detection	Flower Species Classification

LDA vs QDA
Feature	LDA	QDA
Learning Type	Supervised	Supervised
Covariance Matrix	Same for all classes	Different for each class
Decision Boundary	Linear	Quadratic (Curved)
Flexibility	Lower	Higher
Risk of Overfitting	Lower	Higher
Training Data Required	Less	More
Best Used For	Linear datasets	Nonlinear datasets

QDA vs Logistic Regression
Feature	QDA	Logistic Regression
Decision Boundary	Quadratic	Linear
Data Assumption	Gaussian distribution	No Gaussian assumption
Classification	Binary and Multi-class	Binary and Multi-class
Complexity	Higher	Lower
Best For	Nonlinear data	Linearly separable data

Summary
Quadratic Discriminant Analysis (QDA) is a supervised machine learning classification algorithm that extends Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA) by allowing each class to have its own covariance matrix. This enables QDA to create quadratic (curved) decision boundaries, making it more suitable for datasets with nonlinear class separation. QDA can be applied to both binary and multi-class classification problems. Although it requires more training data and computational resources than LDA, it often achieves higher accuracy when class distributions differ significantly. It is widely used in medical diagnosis, image recognition, finance, bioinformatics, and speech recognition.



